            <ArticleTitle>Lid closure mimics head movement in fMRI.</ArticleTitle>
            <Pagination>
                <MedlinePgn>1156-8</MedlinePgn>
            </Pagination>
            <Abstract>
                <AbstractText>Motion correction algorithms are commonly used to correct for involuntary head motions in fMRI. We found that lid closure increased signal intensity of the eyes by a factor of 1.6 to 2 in EPI-fMRI. If the eyes were included in the scanning volume, transitions from eyes open to eyes closed in darkness were regularly associated with erroneously detected head translations along the z-axis and head rotations around the x-axis in Talairach's coordinate system. These artefacts could be avoided by masking the eyes in the images during the estimation of movement parameters.</AbstractText>
            </Abstract>
